Step 2a: Handling missing data¶

  • Missing data must be handled before doing any analysis. It could cause serious issue. For example, when you are calculating the mean of a group of large numbers, NaN might be 0 and the mean will be significantly affected.

Step 2b: Data Transformation¶

  • Sometimes the catgorical data is represented by string. For example, in this dataset sex is marked as male and female. These cotegorical strings does not mean anything in math so we should convert them to numbers. And notice that the magnitude of these numbers could affect the result so we they have the same magnitude. Therefore, we need an identity matrix to hold all features and each vector in this identity matrix represents one unique feature. This method is called one hot encoding.
In [785]:
data.sex.value_counts() #Display the sex distribution of this dataset

male      13910

  • From the result above, we can see that there are in total 101 countries. If I use one-hot encoding to split these countries, there will be too many categories(vectors) which will cause one hot encoding memory error. Therefore I find another way of processing these data which is group countries by continent.
  • The python extension packagep pycountry_convert could help you convert country to continent. You will need to install the packege before importing.
    pip install pycountry-convert.
    This is the link to pycountry_convert api.
  • Unfortunatelly, pycontrv_convert is no powerful enough to recognize the country name in this dataframe, so we will also need to install country_converter to convert all country names to ISO2 format, and then use the function from pycontry_convert to convert the ISO2 country code to continent.
    pip install country_converter --upgrade
    This is the link to country converter api

ax = sns.regplot(x = 'year', y = 'suicide_rate',data = year_df) #plot the linear regression line
  • From the plot we can see that the suicide rate is increasing during 1985 to 1995 and 2015 to 2016, decreasing during 1995 to 2015. At the year 1995, the suicide rate reaches to the history maximun which mean there are nealy 16 out of 100,000 people killed themselves in 1995.
  • The linear regression line indicates that in general the suicide rate is decreasing over time. However, this relationship is not obvious. Therefore, let's add some features to see if we could get some better relationships.

Feature 1: Continent¶

  • Previously we have seen that suicide rate varies among different countries. However, it is too much work to analyze suisde rate in each country. Therefore, instead of nationality, I would like to introduce a more general feature continent to see if this feature would give us some better linear regression lines that indicate the suicide rates over time.
In [803]:
conti_df = data.groupby('continent').mean() # Calculate the average suicide rate for each continent
conti_df = conti_df.sort_values('suicide_rate', ascending=False) #Sort the data in descending order by suicide rate
In [804]:
matplotlib.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [10, 7] #Change the size of the graph
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
plt.title("Average suicide rate for each continent") 
fig = sns.barplot(y=conti_df.index, x=conti_df['suicide_rate']) #Continent names on y axis, suicide rate on x axis
ax.axvline(conti_df['suicide_rate'].mean(), color="green", linewidth=3) #This green line indicates the world average suiside rate
Out[804]:
<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7f6a0f23f2b0>
In [805]:
for conti in conti_df.index:
    #Create a temp dataframe to store the data we want to plot
    curr_conti = data[data.continent == conti]
    curr_year = curr_conti.groupby('year').mean()
    curr_year['year'] = curr_year.index
    curr_year['conti'] = conti
    
    # year on x axis and suicide rate on y axis
    x = curr_year.index
    y = curr_year['suicide_rate']
    
    # Plot
    plt.title('Average Suicide Rate VS. Year in Each Continent')
    ax = sns.scatterplot(x,y,data = curr_year,label = conti)
    ax = sns.regplot(x = 'year', y = 'suicide_rate',data = curr_year, label = conti)
  • This plot indicates that in Europe, Oceania,Asia, Africa and North America, there is a decreasing suicide rate over time. In North America however there is an increasing suicide rate over time.
  • The differences of linear regression lines among each continents indicate that the suicide rate varies in different continent. Therefore continent is a feature that will affect suicide rate.

  • This graph clearly shows that in different age intervals, suiside rate over time is different.
  • For people in age of 5-14, they tends to have a low and constant suicide rate over time. In other words, children keep the good habit of not commit suicides over time.
  • Despite the fact that elders in age of 75+ has the hightest suicide rates among all age intervals, their suicide rate over time is decreasing than any other age intervals. Which means, there is an incresing amount of elders chose not to kill themselves as time goes by.

Step 4: Machine learning for prediction¶

  • Recalll: Our goal is to predict U.S. teenager suicide rate in 2020
  • From part 3, we have seen that suicide rates for male and female are significantly different. Therefore,in order to build a more precise model, we have to add the gender feature to the model.
In [816]:
from sklearn import model_selection
from sklearn import linear_model

Step 4a: Preprocess data¶

  • Data transformation on the categorical data
  • Split the data to training and testing set
In [817]:
ml_data = data.copy() # Create a machine learning data frame to apply some data transformation
ml_data = ml_data[ml_data.country_code == 'US'] # Only use the data that from U.S.
ml_data = ml_data[ml_data.age == '15-24 years'] # Only use the data collect from teenagers(15-24 years)

sex_dummy = pd.get_dummies(data.sex) # Apply one hot encodng on sex column to seperate sex to male and female indicators

ml_data = ml_data.join(sex_dummy) #Merge the sex indicators to our machine learning data frame

ml_data['male_w'] = ml_data['male'] * ml_data.year # Apply year as weight to male indicator
ml_data['female_w'] = ml_data['female'] * ml_data.year # Apply year as weight to female indicator

ml_data.head()

In [818]:
# Cast the data to numpy array
X = np.array(ml_data[['male_w','female_w']]) # Selet weighted sex indicator as the input of our model
y= np.array(ml_data.suicide_rate)# Selet the suicide rate as the result of our model.

#Split the data to training and testing set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = model_selection.train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2)

Step 4b: Train Model¶

  • In part 3, we have seen that there is a linear relationship on suicide rate over time, therefore, we choose to use a linear regression model.
  • Use X_test and y_test tp train our multiple linear regression model
In [819]:
regr = linear_model.LinearRegression()
regr.fit(X_train,y_train)
Out[819]:
LinearRegression(copy_X=True, fit_intercept=True, n_jobs=None, normalize=False)

Step 4c: Test model accuracy¶

  • Use X_test and y_test to calculate the score of our model
In [820]:
regr.score(X_test,y_test)
Out[820]:
0.9475043748245316
  • The score for our multiple linear regression model is 0.95, this is a pretty good score, we could rely on this model to make our prediction.

Step 4d: Predict¶

In [821]:
[male_res] = regr.predict([[2020,0]]) # Predict sucide rate for male in 2020
[female_res] = regr.predict([[0,2020]])# Predict suicide rate for female in 202
print('The suicide rate for U.S. male teenager in 2020 will be ' + str(male_res) + ' per 100k population')
print('The suicide rate for U.S. male teenager in 2020 will be ' + str(female_res) + ' per 100k population')

The suicide rate for U.S. male teenager in 2020 will be 16.79581188470192 per 100k population
The suicide rate for U.S. male teenager in 2020 will be 1.2730288642546554 per 100k population

Step 5: Conclusion¶

In this notebook, I have produced a lot of graphs. It is not hard to see that data visualization is a good and intuitive way to extract hidden information from data. In part 3a(analyze the average suicide rate for each country), I ranked the suicide rate for different country by using a horizontal bar plot; In part 3b(Use Word Cloud for visually presenting the maginitude of suicide rate in each country)I use word clound to make the ranking result even more elegant; In part 3c( Average suiside rate on the world map) I created a choropleth map to show the suicide rate on the world map, the deeper color is, the higher suicide rate will be on that aera. The inofrmation conveyed by these graphs is so clear that could be understood by any one in any country. In part 3d(Average suicide over time), I used a scatter plot and discovered that there is a downward sloping linear relationship between suicide rate and time but this relationship is too general, so we went further to see what are the features that affect the suicide rate and would we get a more clear relationship on suicide rate over time based on those features. Luckily we have found some features that highly related to the suicide rate: continent, age, gender and generation. Then, I applied these features to the suicide rate over time and find some better fit linear regression lines. Most of these linear relationships are downward sloping linear relationships, which mean under these features there is a dercreasing suicide rate over time. However we also find some upward sloping linear relationship. For example, in SA(South and Central America) the suicide rate is increasing over time. This is a important hidden feature I have discovered and this is the reason why we want to analyze data in depth.

The goal of writing this notebook is to predict the U.S. teenager suicide rate in 2020. From the data visualization part, we have discoverd the folllowing facts: 1.There is a decrasing suicide rate over time in general. 2.The suicide rate over time is varied from different country, different geneder and different age. Therefore, to build a precise model, we have to consider some of these features. Instead of using all the data, I chose to extract the data that from U.S. and the age range is on 15-24 years. I am doing this because I want my model tragets on U.S. teenagers so we do not have to add country and age features on the model later on. However, use the targetting data is still not enough to train a good model. Recall from part3d, male suicide rate is much higher than female suicide rate, therefore, we have to add gender feature to our model. I use on-hot encoding method to split the gender feature to gender indicators. It is better for feeding the model and there is no bias between two genders. Finally, I trained my model and got a score of 0.95 which is pretty accurate, I can rely on this model to make our prediction.

Two important things I have learned:

  • Data is never cleaned: Despite I have a whole section (part 2) worked on data cleaning, I still have to sanitize the data before doing some analysis. For example, in the machine learning part, I have to process the categorical data (apply one-hot encoding on sex column so we have male and female indicators); I have to split the data to training set and testing set. However, data cleaning is still very important because in later analysis, it will help spend less time on cleaning data and put more effort on the analyzing.
  • Use more data on training is not always a better choice: We have to understand our goal based on the given inofrmation to find the data that best fits our model. In Step 4(machine learning for prediction), instead of using over 20000 rows of data from the original dataset, I selected 300 rows that highly related to the question and build a model based on those 300 rows of data and as a result I got a descent model with socre 0.95.
